Here is a **clean, ordered, reproducible setup guide** you can follow on another system without running into the same chaos again. I removed unnecessary steps, grouped things logically, and added expected outputs where useful.

---

# OpenClaw Local Agent Setup with Ollama (Step-by-Step)

This guide installs and runs **OpenClaw** locally using a local LLM via **Ollama**.

Recommended lightweight model: **Qwen2.5 0.5B**.

---

# 1. Install Ollama

```bash
curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh
```

Verify installation:

```bash
ollama --version
```

---

# 2. Install and Test a Model

Do **not start with large models** on low RAM machines.

Install a lightweight model:

```bash
ollama pull phi3
```

Test the model:

```bash
ollama run phi3
```

You should see a chat prompt.

Exit:

```
/bye
```

---

# 3. Verify Ollama Server

Ollama usually starts automatically.

Check if it is running:

```bash
curl http://localhost:11434
```

Expected output:

```
Ollama is running
```

Check installed models:

```bash
ollama list
```

---

# 4. Clone OpenClaw Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw.git
cd openclaw
```

---

# 5. Install Node.js

Install Node and npm:

```bash
sudo apt install nodejs npm
```

Check version:

```bash
node -v
```

---

# 6. Install Bun (optional but recommended)

```bash
curl -fsSL https://bun.sh/install | bash
source ~/.bashrc
```

Verify:

```bash
bun -v
```

---

# 7. Install PNPM Package Manager

```bash
sudo npm install -g pnpm
```

Verify:

```bash
pnpm -v
```

---

# 8. Install Node Version Manager (NVM)

OpenClaw requires Node 22+.

Install NVM:

```bash
curl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.40.1/install.sh | bash
```

Reload shell:

```bash
source ~/.bashrc
```

Verify:

```bash
nvm --version
```

---

# 9. Install Node 22

```bash
nvm install 22
nvm use 22
```

Verify:

```bash
node -v
```

Expected output:

```
v22.x.x
```

---

# 10. Install OpenClaw Dependencies

Inside the OpenClaw project:

```bash
pnpm add -Dw tsdown
pnpm install
```

Run development build:

```bash
pnpm dev
```

---

# 11. Setup OpenClaw

Initialize OpenClaw:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs setup
```

Start the gateway:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs gateway
```

Leave this terminal running.

---

# 12. Configure Models (New Terminal)

Scan available models:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs models scan
```

Set the model:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs models set ollama/phi3:latest
```

---

# 13. Configure Authentication

Run:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs models auth add
```

When prompted:

| Prompt         | Value           |
| -------------- | --------------- |
| Token provider | `custom`        |
| Provider id    | `ollama`        |
| Token method   | `paste token`   |
| Profile id     | `ollama:manual` |
| Token expires  | `No`            |
| Token          | `local`         |

This creates an auth profile for Ollama.

Verify configuration:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs models status
```

---

# 14. Install a Tool-Capable Model

Remove old model:

```bash
ollama rm phi3
```

---

## Option A (Large model — may fail on low RAM)

```bash
ollama pull qwen2.5:7b
```

If memory errors occur, use smaller models.

---

## Option B (Recommended for 8GB RAM)

Install:

```bash
ollama pull qwen2.5:3b
```

Set it:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs models set ollama/qwen2.5:3b
```

---

## Option C (Best for low RAM systems)

Install smallest model:

```bash
ollama pull qwen2.5:0.5b
```

Set it:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs models set ollama/qwen2.5:0.5b
```

Verify:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs models status
```

---

# 15. Restart OpenClaw Gateway

Stop gateway:

```
CTRL + C
```

Start again:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs gateway
```

Expected output:

```
[gateway] listening on ws://127.0.0.1:18789
```

---

# 16. Test the Agent

Open a new terminal:

```bash
node scripts/run-node.mjs agent --session-id test --message "hello"
```

Expected response:

```
Assistant: Hello! How can I help you today?
```

---

# 17. Verify Ollama API (Optional)

```bash
curl http://localhost:11434/api/tags
```

You should see installed models in JSON format.

---

